(40, 26, 22, 43, 13, 22, 25, 'Lord, is it I?', 'Disciples'' Doubt and Inquiry', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' sorrow and uncertainty about who would betray Jesus. In Matthew, they each ask, ''Lord, is it I?'', while in John, they express doubt and seek clarification from Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 22, 41, 14, 19, 20, 'Is it I?', 'Sorrowful Inquiry of Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' sorrow and their questioning of their own loyalty to Jesus. The repeated phrase ''Is it I?'' highlights their concern about betrayal. This connection illustrates a shared moment of introspection among the disciples.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 22, 43, 21, 17, 17, 'exceeding sorrowful', 'Connection of Sorrow and Love', 'This connection highlights the theme of personal introspection and emotional response to Jesus'' inquiries. In both passages, the disciples express deep sorrow or grief in relation to their relationship with Jesus, emphasizing their vulnerability and need for reassurance.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 23, 43, 13, 18, 18, 'dippeth his hand with me', 'Betrayal by a Close Associate', 'Both passages emphasize betrayal by someone close to Jesus. The phrase ''dippeth his hand with me'' in Matthew parallels ''eateth bread with me'' in John, highlighting the intimacy of the betrayal.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 23, 19, 41, 9, 9, NULL, 'Betrayal by a Close Friend', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal by a trusted companion. Both passages refer to a familiar friend who has turned against the speaker after sharing a meal.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 23, 43, 13, 26, 28, 'dippeth his hand with me in the dish', 'Connection of Betrayal in Passages', 'Both passages emphasize the act of betrayal by identifying Judas as the one who dips with Jesus. The phrase ''dippeth his hand with me in the dish'' in Matthew parallels the action of Jesus giving the sop to Judas in John, highlighting the moment of betrayal.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 23, 42, 22, 21, 21, 'the same shall betray me', 'Betrayal at the Table', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of the betrayer at the table with Jesus. The phrase ''with me on the table'' in Luke parallels the act of dipping in the dish in Matthew, highlighting the intimate setting of betrayal.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 24, 42, 24, 46, 46, 'it is written', 'Connection of Suffering and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the necessity of suffering for Christ, as indicated in both passages. Matthew emphasizes the betrayal leading to suffering, while Luke underscores that suffering and resurrection were foretold.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 24, 44, 26, 22, 23, 'the Son of man is betrayed', 'Connection of Suffering and Betrayal', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering and betrayal in the context of Christ''s mission. Matthew 26:24 speaks of betrayal leading to dire consequences, while Acts 26:22-23 emphasizes Christ''s suffering and resurrection as foretold by the prophets.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 24, 40, 18, 7, 7, 'woe unto that man', 'Woes of Betrayal and Offense', 'Both passages emphasize the dire consequences of betrayal and offense. They highlight the grave implications for those who cause harm, indicating that it would be better for them not to exist.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
